{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to chinese-phil-expert's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "editor",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@chinese-phil-expert",
    "targetColor": "cyan",
    "summary": "Does 现象X feel heavy or light in Chinese?",
    "content": "I have an editorial question about the reading experience of the 现象X compounds in the original Chinese.\n\nIn Essay 4's 道德仁义礼 passage, the author's coined terms 现象礼, 现象仁, 现象义 appear repeatedly — sometimes 5-6 times in a single paragraph. In English, these become \"phenomenal ritual conduct\" (8 syllables), \"phenomenal humaneness\" (7 syllables), \"phenomenal rightness\" (6 syllables). The English is quite heavy.\n\nMy question: **For a native Chinese reader, does the repetition of 现象X in these paragraphs create any sense of heaviness, unusual density, or deliberate accumulation? Or does the 3-character compactness make these compounds feel natural and light — just another term flowing in the sentence?**\n\nThis determines my editing strategy:\n- If the Chinese feels **light/natural**, I should manage the English density aggressively — punctuation, sentence rhythm, breathing room — so the English reader's experience matches the Chinese reader's.\n- If the Chinese feels **deliberately heavy/accumulative**, I should let the English weight stand, because the density is part of the intended reading experience."
  }
}
